Chapter 1
Cohren
0430 Italiano Time. Cohren hated waking up so early. He especially disliked it because he was responsible for waking up all the others in his company. Silently, he got off his bunk, put on his combat suit, threw on his protective vest, and retrieved his belongings from the locker, being careful around a particular small box. He shouldered his rifle and hung his helmet on a small hook on his belt. Attached to it were everything he needed, such as his breathing apparatus or his special glasses. After checking his ammunition pouches, he quietly left the barracks. Outside, the mud and ice crunched under his boots.
He took a match from one jacket pocket and a cigarette from the other. He lit it and took a short drag before opening the door slightly. Last week, he had had to come up with various ways to wake the men and women under his command. He no longer used the preset alarm clock, as it usually didn't work and only produced a faint hissing sound from the speakers.
"Wake them up?" Cohren turned around and saw Zugführer Nemic approaching him.
"Yes," Cohren replied.
"What do you want to try this time?"
Before he could answer, the door opened and Harris, Craith, and a few others came towards him already dressed in full gear.
"Good morning," said Craith.
"What woke you up, then?"
"Firstly, we didn't feel like waiting for whatever you've come up with today. And secondly, the assault troops who rise first get to choose the morning ration," replied one of the men, Ravik. "And you know how bad the food can be."
"Good point, Sergeant," said Cohren. He reached in and pressed a switch. A loud, shrill alarm echoed through the barracks. Inside, he heard muted curses and people scrambling around.
"Come on, Valturi," said Nemic. "One would think they would have learned to wake up at the same time as you by now."
"Well, my guys from the training camp have learned it," Cohren replied and pointed at Harris, Craith, and Ravik. "However, the platoon and section leaders also know that they have to wake up before their units."
Seconds later, the rest of the company emerged. They had everything they needed, from personal items to the necessary equipment. Some of the newer recruits looked confused, while others appeared irritated.
"Good morning," said Cohren cheerfully.
"With all due respect, sir, why do you have to wake us up like this?" asked a Sergeant from the assault troops.
"Because the regular alarms suck and because Daybreak doesn't oversleep," said Cohren.
"Pack all your personal items," Cohren continued. As the senior lieutenant and executive officer of the company, he was responsible for overseeing and supporting them together with the company commander, Hauptmann Boradin Shaw. "We will not return here. Sergeants and lieutenants, you and your squads have fifteen minutes for the final checks and to pack the daily rations."
The members of the Exodus Company dispersed quickly. They were part of the second assault troop division, second army. Before they were consolidated, they were two companies, Cohort and Dagger. The company was split, and that was the main reason why Cohren had mixed feelings about his promotion to senior lieutenant.
Cohren and Nemic, the leader of the first platoon, walked side by side under the light of many generator-powered lamps of the forward deployment base. Most of them had red-tinted glass to avoid detection by enemy bombers. Daybreak had resorted to Wild-Weasel attacks from the air and ground to counter them.
"A new day and a new task for the Hellhounds," Nemic said with a dry laugh. "Where are they sending us?"
"A forward deployment base outside Ianlos. We'll support the ground attack," Cohren replied, drawing on his cigarette. He attributed part of the blame for his smoking to Craith, but a year in service changed one, so he said nothing.
"Fucking hell. Things are getting worse at the front," murmured Nemic. "All the news reads: 'Support the war effort. Send help to the Kurgan front.' What about the Howland front?"
"Amen, brother," said Cohren, flicking the ashes of his cigarette into the mud. "At least we're starting with the first armed column and don't have to run. Captain Shaw should already be there."
"Shaw has made us a ride available?" Nemic asked a bit surprised.
"Yes. He is actually not as bad as I thought. Not particularly friendly, but one can put up with him."
Cohren raised his thumb and index finger to his throat mic and adjusted his backpack. "All units of the Exodus Company gather at the West Vehicle Park when you're ready. We depart with the first armed column at 0500."
In quick succession, he received responses from the section leaders. Harris, Craith, and Ravik were non-commissioned officers of low rank when they all arrived here. The four had been close friends since their return to Earth. Cohren felt as if he had known them forever, although it had only been two years. They were section leaders, but Craith had taken command of the second platoon a week ago, after its previous leader was medically discharged following an assassination attempt by a Daybreak sniper.
On the way to the vehicle park, Cohren and Nemic noticed a group of about eight Kronos battle tanks and four infantry fighting vehicles. Their crews roamed around, ensuring their machines were ready for action. Quickly, Cohren spotted Hauptmann Boradin Shaw, who was speaking with the commander of the armed column. As they approached, Shaw looked over at them and came toward them, as usual with a blank expression.
"Lieutenant Nemic... Lieutenant Valturi..." He said, noting that Cohren was slower as he looked at Cohren's pistol holster and then back up. "I assume the company is ready?"
